This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it focuses on quantizing convolutional neural networks for efficient and accurate inference. It also involves experimentation on different datasets and networks, which are commonly used in computer vision tasks. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of convolutional layers, which are a fundamental component of many computer vision models. 

The paper also involves machine learning techniques, such as learning to optimally quantize the weights and activations of the network during training, and a new training technique called gradual quantization. Therefore, it is also likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. 

Furthermore, the paper discusses the potential of this approach for neural network accelerators on the edge, which falls under the neural engineering (cs.NE) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper proposes a strategy to improve network performance under noisy conditions, which is relevant to the robotics (cs.RO) and automation and control (cs.AC) sub-categories. However, given the focus of the paper on computer vision and machine learning, these sub-categories are less likely than the previously mentioned ones.
